1
00:00:01,145 --> 00:00:10,143
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

2
00:00:11,826 --> 00:00:21,144
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

3
00:00:22,929 --> 00:00:39,689
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:42,926 --> 00:00:45,270
Now we've come to the end of the seventh day.

5
00:00:46,030 --> 00:00:51,176
We're well into the course, well adjusted, in fact, having a great time.

6
00:00:52,158 --> 00:00:52,959
How else could it be?

7
00:00:52,999 --> 00:01:02,871
I'm sure that those who will leave but tomorrow will now regret bitterly that they will not be staying or have not stayed for the full eight weeks.

8
00:01:04,552 --> 00:01:11,061
The fact is that once you've got through the first seven days, you can actually keep going with very little effort.

9
00:01:12,155 --> 00:01:19,885
It's also true that those staying for three weeks or more can train themselves to sleep less, down to three and a half or four hours a night.

10
00:01:21,667 --> 00:01:33,100
When a meditator does that, they experience the next three days similar to when they started, going through the healing torture of raising energy one more notch.

11
00:01:34,423 --> 00:01:40,390
If after five days they still feel exhausted during the day, then it's okay to go back to five and a half hours.

12
00:01:41,617 --> 00:01:52,132
The fact we can do with less sleep during a meditation course is because of the purifying effect and the transformative effect of the practice.

13
00:01:52,152 --> 00:02:08,453
The practice lets mental turbulences release themselves and transforms that violent energy into a pure calm flow as when water having bubbled and boiled over rapids transforms into a deep and powerful gentle river.

14
00:02:10,170 --> 00:02:11,051
But why do this?

15
00:02:12,052 --> 00:02:13,895
I mean, why do we have to lift energy?

16
00:02:15,317 --> 00:02:19,201
Because in so doing, we squeeze the hidden turbulence out of the system.

17
00:02:20,264 --> 00:02:23,247
Remember, this turbulence also turns inwards.

18
00:02:23,728 --> 00:02:36,364
It drags us down and causes us to feel that dullness and lethargy, as when water trapped is overgrown with weeds and often turns fetid and rank.

19
00:02:36,343 --> 00:02:46,557
But when we refuse to go down but stay awake, that deeper layer of turbulence begins to manifest as some form of mental turbulence.

20
00:02:46,578 --> 00:02:49,802
And so we can work with that deeper layer of our psychology.

21
00:02:50,604 --> 00:02:55,090
So though staying on for three weeks or more, let's see if we can lift our energy.

22
00:02:57,332 --> 00:03:03,480
Now all this week we've been looking inward and trying to understand how suffering arises and how it passes away.

23
00:03:03,540 --> 00:03:06,164
Indeed, that is what we mean by karma.

24
00:03:07,799 --> 00:03:17,014
You will notice, by the way, I am using the more common Sanskrit form of the word with the R, karma, which is now in the Oxford English Dictionary.

25
00:03:18,257 --> 00:03:22,764
In the Theravada Pali script it doesn't have an R, kamma.

26
00:03:22,784 --> 00:03:30,498
But that aside, we need to understand the Buddha's teaching around karma so that we can take our practice into ordinary daily life.

27
00:03:32,503 --> 00:03:38,152
First, it's important to understand the underlying philosophy of causality, cause and effect.

28
00:03:39,474 --> 00:03:44,503
As we all know, and as our science understands, nothing comes into existence without a cause.

29
00:03:45,444 --> 00:03:47,228
Nothing happens without causes.

30
00:03:48,270 --> 00:03:52,295
What happens is the effect, the consequence, of some past action or event.

31
00:03:53,138 --> 00:03:54,580
That's our usual understanding.

32
00:03:55,876 --> 00:04:02,883
Remembering our iconic toast, once that lever is pressed, we know the bread will be transformed.

33
00:04:04,366 --> 00:04:13,556
Equally, when one of those terrible diseases hits the animal population, mad cow disease or foot and mouth, scientists set about searching for the cause.

34
00:04:14,798 --> 00:04:20,043
We sometimes go far back in time to understand the cause of present day events, such as an earthquake.

35
00:04:21,357 --> 00:04:26,745
We try to see our present psychological problems in terms of what happened to us in childhood, and so on.

36
00:04:28,187 --> 00:04:30,572
The Buddha stated this in a very simple way.

37
00:04:31,713 --> 00:04:37,122
Literally, the Pali translates as, Because that arose, this is now arising.

38
00:04:37,704 --> 00:04:41,610
Because that did not arise, this does not arise now.

39
00:04:42,956 --> 00:04:45,040
Here we have a more subtle understanding.

40
00:04:45,779 --> 00:04:48,343
We tend to look at karma only in the positive.

41
00:04:49,384 --> 00:04:52,307
This happened to me because that happened previously.

42
00:04:52,327 --> 00:04:57,595
I got my wages at the end of the week because I worked.

43
00:04:57,615 --> 00:04:59,317
But the negative is also true.

44
00:05:00,057 --> 00:05:04,223
I didn't make any money this week because I was sick and couldn't work.

45
00:05:06,228 --> 00:05:09,831
Because we do support a worthy cause, some benefit arises.

46
00:05:11,052 --> 00:05:14,916
Because we fail to do so, some benefit fails to materialize.

47
00:05:17,218 --> 00:05:26,608
Now if everything that happens now is indeed caused by some past event, that suggests everything is set, predetermined, everything is fate.

48
00:05:28,151 --> 00:05:30,192
Where then would choice and free will figure?

49
00:05:31,776 --> 00:05:37,004
What's more, if indeed everything is determined by past events, where does creativity come in?

50
00:05:38,406 --> 00:05:42,694
Surely we'd be looking at a universe constantly repeating set patterns.

51
00:05:43,836 --> 00:05:46,339
The same cause and effect spinning around each other.

52
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:48,283
A monotonous dance.

53
00:05:50,625 --> 00:06:02,444
The Buddha points out that things also happen because of a conjunction, a meeting of various lines of actions that come from various past causes to create a single new event.

54
00:06:04,869 --> 00:06:07,593
Jung, the psychologist, called this synchronicity.

55
00:06:09,136 --> 00:06:17,410
Again, the Pali translates literally as because this is, so that is, because this is not, so that is not.

56
00:06:18,992 --> 00:06:26,783
For a person to receive their wages either in hand or in the bank account takes a lot of things to come together from various sources.

57
00:06:28,266 --> 00:06:37,759
There's the amount of work done, the registering of it, which implies all the office work, the transfer of money, which implies all the banking system, and so on.

58
00:06:39,822 --> 00:06:44,949
I shall spare you the details of how a piece of toast ends up succulent on the tongue.

59
00:06:47,377 --> 00:06:51,060
Here we have an understanding that is reflected in modern chaos theory.

60
00:06:52,081 --> 00:07:02,050
Dependent on supporting conditions, it may be that a flap of a butterfly wing in the tropics could eventually develop into a tornado in little old UK.

61
00:07:03,112 --> 00:07:13,822
That is, supporting conditions of weather patterns may come from different sources to conspire, as it were, to use that little flapping as a catalyst to create a catastrophe.

62
00:07:15,017 --> 00:07:21,709
By the way, I find it typical of our present-day gloom and doom that a positive spin could not be given to it.

63
00:07:22,672 --> 00:07:25,076
Conditions creating a great summer, for instance.

64
00:07:27,079 --> 00:07:30,406
It is also important to take this understanding into our moral behaviour.

65
00:07:31,127 --> 00:07:38,882
A small act of kindness whirled by supporting conditions may bring an end to an age-old quarrel, an age-old war.

66
00:07:40,718 --> 00:07:55,494
Now if it were true that the universe was only a confluence of unrelated events, different events totally unconnected with each other in the present and arising with no connection to the past, then we can imagine only chaos, real chaos.

67
00:07:56,475 --> 00:07:58,117
How could there be any coherence?

68
00:07:59,458 --> 00:08:04,584
Or if there were, it would be by mere chance, and then only for the occasional moment.

69
00:08:05,685 --> 00:08:09,408
Yet without these haphazard meetings, there can be no creativity.

70
00:08:10,620 --> 00:08:19,295
We may unexpectedly meet a friend and suddenly a choice arises whether to do something with our friend or carry on doing what we'd set out to do.

71
00:08:20,858 --> 00:08:22,141
I set out looking for work.

72
00:08:22,781 --> 00:08:24,285
Others are looking for workers.

73
00:08:24,485 --> 00:08:25,547
Opportunities arise.

74
00:08:26,208 --> 00:08:28,411
Some improbable, some just up my street.

75
00:08:28,833 --> 00:08:29,213
Hopefully.

76
00:08:31,476 --> 00:08:35,784
So to understand the picture fully, we need to blend these two positions together.

77
00:08:37,063 --> 00:08:46,695
Something happens now because the different parts of that event come from a structured past and because they happen to all come together at one and the same time.

78
00:08:49,158 --> 00:09:05,417
Even in this statement we do not catch the boggling complexity of the situation because what the term structured past fails to get across is the idea that every moment in that structured past was a similar confluence of various karmic lines.

79
00:09:07,101 --> 00:09:12,669
There is the story of the boy who was drowning in a bog and the local poor farmer who saved him.

80
00:09:13,951 --> 00:09:17,557
The rich father of that boy wanted to give the farmer some money.

81
00:09:18,717 --> 00:09:20,240
The farmer would have nothing to do with it.

82
00:09:21,702 --> 00:09:25,006
So the rich man offered to give the poor man's son an education.

83
00:09:26,469 --> 00:09:34,880
As things turned out, the rich man's son was Winston Churchill and the poor man's son was Alexander Fleming, the discoverer of penicillin.

84
00:09:36,615 --> 00:09:44,008
When Winston Churchill fell ill with pneumonia, it was Fleming's penicillin that saved him, saved twice by the same family.

85
00:09:45,671 --> 00:09:53,263
Here we see a graphic example of the interaction of two differing lines of past karma meeting to create unexpected results.

86
00:09:54,904 --> 00:09:59,653
What possible connection could there have been originally between the poor and the rich boy?

87
00:10:00,982 --> 00:10:07,350
There will be those who argue that this was the product of karma coming from a past life, and there may be some truth in that.

88
00:10:08,471 --> 00:10:10,332
But I tend to lean on the side of chance.

89
00:10:11,754 --> 00:10:17,480
Our general disposition is to try to make sense of everything, even if it does not solve the problem.

90
00:10:18,722 --> 00:10:25,590
To be sick and not know what is wrong with you is worse than finding out what is wrong but can't be cured.

91
00:10:26,471 --> 00:10:27,952
One learns to bear with it.

92
00:10:28,490 --> 00:10:31,272
Even if it's terminal, one can come to terms with it.

93
00:10:32,133 --> 00:10:35,816
But not knowing is an anxious and frustrating place for us to be.

94
00:10:35,855 --> 00:10:42,782
And as we shall see, there are other laws that really do bring that element of chance into our lives.

95
00:10:45,325 --> 00:10:50,769
So here we have the basic law underlying the teachings of karma, the law of conditionality.

96
00:10:52,009 --> 00:10:57,315
Everything arises in the present moment dependent on past and present conditions.

97
00:10:58,527 --> 00:11:01,409
Nothing arises spontaneously of its own cause.

98
00:11:02,551 --> 00:11:08,537
There is nothing causeless in the relative universe simply because everything is related.

99
00:11:10,639 --> 00:11:18,287
You can see, though that this is not a mechanical law, we don't live in a simple one-and-one-makes-two logical universe.

100
00:11:19,187 --> 00:11:24,754
There's something quite unpredictable about the universe and indeed about our lives as human beings.

101
00:11:26,083 --> 00:11:30,850
In fact, the Buddha said, if you were to try to work out your karma, it would drive you mad.

102
00:11:33,595 --> 00:11:38,761
To give you a sense of what it's all about, I'd like to ask you to practice a little visualization with me.

103
00:11:39,562 --> 00:11:42,827
You'll have to close your eyes for this one, and imagine.

104
00:11:42,868 --> 00:11:50,217
Imagine there's a little puddle, and a tiny stone lands in the center of it.

105
00:11:51,211 --> 00:11:56,177
See how the waves expand outwards, hit the edge and flow back to the centre.

106
00:11:57,679 --> 00:12:01,144
And how this continues until the momentum slowly dies away.

107
00:12:03,748 --> 00:12:07,513
Now see that puddle showered with little stones of various sizes.

108
00:12:08,053 --> 00:12:09,255
Can you see the turmoil?

109
00:12:10,017 --> 00:12:11,938
And yet there's that underlying pattern.

110
00:12:12,821 --> 00:12:17,346
As waves criss-cross, there are new meetings, each wave affecting the other.

111
00:12:17,967 --> 00:12:19,750
Everything is interconnected.

112
00:12:22,682 --> 00:12:27,389
Now take a large pool and place that puddle in some quiet little corner.

113
00:12:28,591 --> 00:12:38,003
Again see how the stone creates a wave that flows out to the edge and back again and also flows against that little puddle and affects all the wavelets there.

114
00:12:40,767 --> 00:12:48,437
Now shower that pool with stones of various sizes and again see the apparent turmoil and the underlying structure.

115
00:12:50,947 --> 00:13:06,994
Now take a large lake and place that pool with its puddle in a hidden corner and again watch that first wave splash out from the centre and make its way to the bank and back, again affecting all the waves in the pool with its little puddle.

116
00:13:10,740 --> 00:13:13,144
Again shower the lake with rocks and boulders.

117
00:13:14,306 --> 00:13:15,268
Oh, what a creation!

118
00:13:18,116 --> 00:13:23,323
Now take a sea and again place that lake with its pond and puddle in some quiet corner.

119
00:13:24,465 --> 00:13:31,714
Again, see that first splash and the wave launching out to the surrounding beach, crossing over the lake, the pool and the puddle.

120
00:13:35,798 --> 00:13:39,283
And now again the sea is bombarded with pebbles, rocks and boulders.

121
00:13:41,125 --> 00:13:41,846
What mayhem!

122
00:13:46,837 --> 00:13:48,480
And finally the vast ocean.

123
00:13:49,260 --> 00:13:53,586
Hidden somewhere is that sea containing the lake, the pool and the puddle.

124
00:13:54,506 --> 00:13:55,727
Again a great wave.

125
00:13:56,469 --> 00:14:01,754
Watch it flow outward and as it lifts the pool and the puddle it hardly affects them, so great is it.

126
00:14:02,534 --> 00:14:05,118
Both are simply lifted up in the great swell.

127
00:14:09,082 --> 00:14:11,125
And again so many swells.

128
00:14:13,669 --> 00:14:14,812
And one last little thing.

129
00:14:15,854 --> 00:14:21,424
Focus again on that little puddle and notice that the turbulent which hits it does not penetrate.

130
00:14:21,784 --> 00:14:26,053
It only causes the inner water to vibrate as when we strike a balloon.

131
00:14:26,073 --> 00:14:34,750
And as you slowly zoom away, you notice it's intimately surrounded by lots of other little puddles.

132
00:14:38,053 --> 00:14:39,375
And one final observation.

133
00:14:40,017 --> 00:14:41,538
Waves are not water moving.

134
00:14:41,919 --> 00:14:49,551
It is simply a force that runs through the mass, causing it to rise and fall.

135
00:14:49,571 --> 00:14:50,793
So now there's our image.

136
00:14:51,433 --> 00:14:57,043
It's a way of symbolizing how each of us are at a crossroads of lesser or greater confluences.

137
00:14:58,144 --> 00:15:03,251
And what we need to be very clear about is what constitutes karma, personal karma.

138
00:15:03,417 --> 00:15:09,942
That karma that has to be cleared up, purified and refined as a part of the process of becoming liberated.

139
00:15:12,245 --> 00:15:17,610
We can take these images in various ways to see how intricately complicated the universe is.

140
00:15:18,510 --> 00:15:30,623
On the grand scale we can see the puddles as human beings, the pool, the society we create, the lake, the earth we live on, the sea, our galaxy and the ocean, the vast cosmos.

141
00:15:31,936 --> 00:15:47,390
Alternatively, we can take it on a more interactive human level, making the puddle stand for individuals, the pool for the family and relatives, the lake for our society, the sea for our culture, and the ocean for mankind.

142
00:15:49,994 --> 00:16:00,423
Here we have used the word karma in a more popular way to describe how all things come to be, all cause and effect, but the teachings make a finer distinction.

143
00:16:01,788 --> 00:16:03,630
They point to five different laws.

144
00:16:04,812 --> 00:16:06,976
They equate with our own modern understandings.

145
00:16:07,938 --> 00:16:10,003
The first are the physical laws of nature.

146
00:16:11,465 --> 00:16:14,250
Luckily, we live in a fairly benevolent climate.

147
00:16:15,011 --> 00:16:24,589
Some parts of the world suffer greatly from floods and droughts, and perhaps most dramatic of all in recent times, earthquakes, hurricanes and tsunamis.

148
00:16:25,986 --> 00:16:29,812
Yet even we in temperate climes are affected in all sorts of ways by the weather.

149
00:16:30,732 --> 00:16:33,517
How the cold and dark of winter keeps us indoors.

150
00:16:34,619 --> 00:16:39,485
At an extreme level some people suffer from depression because of light deprivation.

151
00:16:41,126 --> 00:16:43,470
It's the time we prefer to catch colds and flus.

152
00:16:45,092 --> 00:16:49,238
And then summer with its flowers and sun, more than occasional these days, happily.

153
00:16:50,220 --> 00:16:52,062
How we love to bask in the warmth.

154
00:16:53,375 --> 00:16:58,120
how a sunny day lays us out on beaches like pancakes, and so on.

155
00:16:59,160 --> 00:17:08,589
But it's much bigger than that, how dependent we are on that very sun, how inexorably tied up we are with the laws that govern the physical universe.

156
00:17:09,611 --> 00:17:15,636
Who knows what distant galactic explosion might not blast this puny little planet out of existence.

157
00:17:16,698 --> 00:17:18,059
Not to talk of black holes.

158
00:17:19,141 --> 00:17:21,323
Now there I go being gloomy and doomy,

159
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:33,051
Alternatively, it may remain a favoured place for the evolution of consciousness and simply die away gracefully with the rest of the universe.

160
00:17:33,071 --> 00:17:35,834
In popular Buddhism, there is much confusion over this.

161
00:17:36,275 --> 00:17:44,682
Much like the monotheistic religions, people believe that storms and earthquakes and tsunamis are sent to us by our past karma, our sins.

162
00:17:45,584 --> 00:17:51,309
Not because there is some judging God doing it, but because of the lord of cause and effect, karma.

163
00:17:53,415 --> 00:18:00,003
There's a telling story, a later attachment to one of the verses of the Dhammapada, the collection of the Buddha's sayings.

164
00:18:01,686 --> 00:18:03,628
A ship suddenly stops in the middle of the sea.

165
00:18:04,549 --> 00:18:05,711
The wind suddenly drops.

166
00:18:06,673 --> 00:18:08,535
The captain and crew are mystified.

167
00:18:09,557 --> 00:18:13,582
Luckily, there's a group of monks on board who have supranormal powers.

168
00:18:14,702 --> 00:18:23,253
They sit in meditation and announce to all that the reason the ship has stopped is because of the bad karma of the captain's wife.

169
00:18:23,807 --> 00:18:30,538
It seems that in a past life she drowned many dogs, and there would be no sailing until she left the ship.

170
00:18:32,181 --> 00:18:33,303
Can you imagine how she felt?

171
00:18:34,585 --> 00:18:35,405
Worse was to come.

172
00:18:36,407 --> 00:18:38,330
How could she leave the ship in the middle of the sea?

173
00:18:39,333 --> 00:18:42,837
There was only one way for it, so they chucked her overboard.

174
00:18:44,260 --> 00:18:48,988
The wind blew, the ship quickly caught sail, and soon made harbour.

175
00:18:51,195 --> 00:18:55,741
The next is concerned with the law of seeds, as it translates.

176
00:18:57,084 --> 00:18:59,207
This is anything to do with life, with biology.

177
00:18:59,587 --> 00:19:01,790
As for humans, that refers to our DNA.

178
00:19:02,731 --> 00:19:04,775
And here lies another regular misconception.

179
00:19:05,896 --> 00:19:12,125
It does say clearly in the discourses that the way we behave morally has an effect on the way we look.

180
00:19:12,144 --> 00:19:16,191
Hatefulness leads to an ugliness, love and joy to a beauty.

181
00:19:17,555 --> 00:19:20,438
but our dispositions are only one in a number of factors.

182
00:19:21,398 --> 00:19:26,525
The overriding factor must be our genetic makeup, which comes to us from a long history of evolution.

183
00:19:27,567 --> 00:19:38,680
So we should hardly feel that we're undergoing the consequences of a hateful heart in the past life, if we happen in this life to look like the back of a bus.

184
00:19:38,700 --> 00:19:43,224
So what is our actual true karma in terms of the process of awakening?

185
00:19:44,605 --> 00:19:48,329
It is how we deal with being plain or plain ugly.

186
00:19:49,612 --> 00:19:54,699
Even though ugliness and beauty are all to do with human convention, nonetheless they affect us.

187
00:19:56,020 --> 00:20:04,633
In the same way as ugliness, for instance, might lead to low self-esteem, beauty can lead to conceit, both unskillful, unwholesome.

188
00:20:05,694 --> 00:20:09,599
Ultimately, of course, how we look should not be of any consequence to us.

189
00:20:10,846 --> 00:20:14,971
But the fact remains, however, that the way we feel does have an effect on our looks.

190
00:20:15,672 --> 00:20:22,098
Not simply body language, but even the shape the face grows into can express a constant underlying mood.

191
00:20:22,980 --> 00:20:24,481
Depression or joy, for instance.

192
00:20:25,983 --> 00:20:31,769
Even so, the body we have is not something we have directly caused by our actions.

193
00:20:34,073 --> 00:20:36,516
The third law is the law concerning the mind.

194
00:20:37,761 --> 00:20:48,538
Again, this tends to focus on how the mind works, how consciousness arises and contacts the world and so on, and especially the psychology of dependent origination we've covered.

195
00:20:50,121 --> 00:20:53,026
But implied, of course, is our relationship to the world around us.

196
00:20:54,248 --> 00:20:58,094
Was it a conscious choice to be born into the family we were brought up in?

197
00:20:59,115 --> 00:21:02,200
Did we make a decision to be born in this country and not another?

198
00:21:03,496 --> 00:21:10,505
How all overpowering on our minds and hearts, our personality and character is the family and society we are born into.

199
00:21:11,987 --> 00:21:19,376
The way we see things, talk about things, our opinions, even the very language we use has been pre-set, pre-determined for us.

200
00:21:20,498 --> 00:21:27,106
We are born into a set of values, a history, a culture and a civilization.

201
00:21:27,289 --> 00:21:29,053
we are profoundly conditioned by them.

202
00:21:29,875 --> 00:21:35,967
Indeed, how else can we be human beings if not as members of a family and a country with all that that implies?

203
00:21:37,509 --> 00:21:40,474
Has it all been the result of my own personal past actions?

204
00:21:41,257 --> 00:21:41,656
Hardly.

205
00:21:42,578 --> 00:21:47,188
Yet here I am with an identity that firmly locks me into time and place.

206
00:21:48,501 --> 00:21:55,053
Again, there is some connection, but not necessarily because of a personal action, moral or otherwise.

207
00:21:56,114 --> 00:21:58,659
It may be just the way things came together.

208
00:22:00,821 --> 00:22:07,573
Then there's the Dharma, often translated as the law or the norm, the truth as to the way things really are.

209
00:22:08,701 --> 00:22:23,382
Penetrating the world within, our feelings, thoughts and emotions, and the world without, living organisms and the material universe, are the spiritual truths that teach us about our relationship to this interior and exterior life.

210
00:22:24,723 --> 00:22:31,534
And within these teachings, that are only concerned to liberate us from suffering, lies the law of karma itself.

211
00:22:33,897 --> 00:22:38,403
So what did the Buddha mean by karma, specific to the process of liberation?

212
00:22:39,717 --> 00:22:41,659
Karma here means action, what we do.

213
00:22:42,759 --> 00:22:47,566
It's not to be confused with the result of action, which is properly termed viparka.

214
00:22:49,126 --> 00:22:51,470
But what is it that actually creates an action?

215
00:22:52,590 --> 00:22:53,291
Is it not will?

216
00:22:54,452 --> 00:23:00,298
Just consider what happens when we do walking meditation, or indeed anything on an intensive course like this.

217
00:23:01,820 --> 00:23:06,365
We first try to become aware of our intentions before we actually act them out.

218
00:23:07,577 --> 00:23:13,303
This has been a very important part of our training because usually we don't distinguish between the two.

219
00:23:14,463 --> 00:23:17,926
In ordinary daily life we rarely stop to consider an intention.

220
00:23:18,807 --> 00:23:21,529
As soon as the desire arises we tend to act upon it.

221
00:23:22,730 --> 00:23:27,756
Who would want to pause and note the intention to open a door once they've decided to leave a room?

222
00:23:29,336 --> 00:23:35,241
It's normally when we're in a state of doubt or conflict do we consider whether to respond to an intention or not.

223
00:23:36,222 --> 00:23:37,263
Usually we just react.

224
00:23:38,392 --> 00:23:43,457
But until we've begun to meditate, we may not have realized the crucial role of will.

225
00:23:44,657 --> 00:23:52,224
For will is that power that brings something out of potential into the actual, within ourselves and into the world.

226
00:23:54,027 --> 00:23:57,410
If a thought comes to mind, I need not necessarily follow it.

227
00:23:58,391 --> 00:24:04,517
To cause it to continue means something has been added to the original impetus, the original stimulus.

228
00:24:05,627 --> 00:24:07,971
Perhaps an image of someone I dislike arises.

229
00:24:08,752 --> 00:24:09,974
I could just stop it there.

230
00:24:11,016 --> 00:24:12,898
Something must empower it to develop.

231
00:24:14,201 --> 00:24:17,567
Perhaps an idea comes to take a holiday in an exotic place.

232
00:24:18,828 --> 00:24:22,653
It could stop there, or I may end up right where I had imagined.

233
00:24:24,718 --> 00:24:29,424
What is it that empowered that desire in my mind to throw it into the world out there?

234
00:24:30,838 --> 00:24:34,047
That empowering is what the Buddha meant by will.

235
00:24:34,788 --> 00:24:42,807
And he goes so far as to say, Disciples, it is the will, cetana, that I call karma.

236
00:24:44,827 --> 00:24:48,252
So will is the power that brings potential into actual.

237
00:24:49,134 --> 00:24:50,636
It is that which conditions.

238
00:24:51,597 --> 00:24:55,585
It is the will that has created this inner environment that we live in.

239
00:24:56,566 --> 00:25:07,061
It is the will that has created and is developing right now all our emotions and thoughts, and it is our will, our will to live, that keeps this body alive.

240
00:25:08,625 --> 00:25:11,950
It is activated in a conscious way when we deliberate,

241
00:25:12,267 --> 00:25:18,476
but it is active also in an unconscious way out of habit for the will itself is also conditioned.

242
00:25:19,778 --> 00:25:23,604
That's why we can teach ourselves to do something even when we're not watching.

243
00:25:24,746 --> 00:25:31,736
I'm sure you've experienced coming back from a daydream to find the mind happily noting rising, falling.

244
00:25:33,898 --> 00:25:38,306
Now from an intention there arises through the empowering of will an action.

245
00:25:39,548 --> 00:25:41,109
Many actions form a habit.

246
00:25:42,051 --> 00:25:48,222
Many habits form a personality and character, and once you've got that, well, you've also got your destiny.

247
00:25:49,766 --> 00:25:57,661
The crucial link in the chain is the movement out of intention into action, be it a thought, word, or deed.

248
00:25:59,503 --> 00:26:03,351
So how does this psychology link in with the end of suffering?

249
00:26:05,136 --> 00:26:10,285
First let us remember that will does not have understanding, it's just a power.

250
00:26:11,105 --> 00:26:13,568
What guides our will is the way we see things.

251
00:26:14,590 --> 00:26:19,979
It is our understanding, deluded or wise, that commands the will to empower a desire.

252
00:26:21,520 --> 00:26:30,974
Although there are many times we perform neutral actions, such as tying up our shoelaces, a lot of the time we could ask ourselves whether something is skillful or not.

253
00:26:33,335 --> 00:26:40,037
Now here, we must make a distinction between the moral and the skillful, the immoral and the unskillful.

254
00:26:41,721 --> 00:26:43,904
All of us have given up gross, immoral behaviour.

255
00:26:44,766 --> 00:26:45,185
Have we not?

256
00:26:46,228 --> 00:26:49,791
I mean, we're not about to kill or steal or tell whoppers.

257
00:26:49,811 --> 00:26:57,161
No doubt we infringe the moral law in some small aspects, little piccadillos, but nothing to get us in serious trouble with the police.

258
00:26:58,242 --> 00:27:01,727
But when it comes to skilfulness, well, we've a long way to go.

259
00:27:03,028 --> 00:27:06,413
By Kusala, skilful, wholesome, virtuous...

260
00:27:06,393 --> 00:27:10,660
The Buddha meant all those actions that lead us to the end of suffering, Nibbana.

261
00:27:11,741 --> 00:27:16,809
The path leading to that liberation is always against the flow self would have us follow.

262
00:27:18,372 --> 00:27:26,885
Before the Buddha took his seat beneath the Bodhi tree, where he was to become enlightened, he put his bowl in the river and it flowed upstream.

263
00:27:28,268 --> 00:27:34,037
It's a metaphorical way to show that the path of enlightenment is against our self-conditioned will.

264
00:27:35,164 --> 00:27:40,954
There's a verse in the Dhammapada which says that those who are not mindful, not skillful, are as if dead.

265
00:27:41,415 --> 00:27:44,741
So beware, only dead fish go with the flow.

266
00:27:46,586 --> 00:27:53,637
To turn that self-conditioning around and to follow the desires of the Dharma is what spiritual training is all about.

267
00:27:55,101 --> 00:27:59,568
The whole of spiritual training could be said to be the reconditioning of the will.

268
00:27:59,650 --> 00:28:09,423
For once the will is behind the desire to become enlightened, awakened, then it becomes known as Dhammachetana, the will that follows the true law.

269
00:28:10,365 --> 00:28:15,330
What in Mahayana is called Bodhicitta, the mind bent on enlightenment.

270
00:28:16,553 --> 00:28:18,615
Now when that happens, the path is straightened up.

271
00:28:19,557 --> 00:28:26,046
No more side alleys, no more diversions, no more wanderings in the garden of lotus eaters.

272
00:28:28,304 --> 00:28:34,951
And this is when we come to understand the importance of renunciation in our spiritual practice.

273
00:28:34,971 --> 00:28:44,221
Renunciation must not be confused with self-mortification if what we mean by self-mortification is to make ourselves suffer in order to get rid of suffering.

274
00:28:45,564 --> 00:28:50,009
The Buddha discovered that to be simply painful, ignoble and unprofitable.

275
00:28:51,289 --> 00:28:53,011
It gets you nowhere but into more suffering.

276
00:28:54,173 --> 00:29:00,699
Renunciation, on the other hand, is the practice of confronting unskillful will, unskillful conditioning.

277
00:29:01,859 --> 00:29:06,964
It's the process whereby we undo self-conditioning and create a dharma conditioning.

278
00:29:08,846 --> 00:29:10,468
Today, lots of people diet.

279
00:29:11,028 --> 00:29:11,308
Why?

280
00:29:11,328 --> 00:29:13,851
Is it not to contain their greed?

281
00:29:15,031 --> 00:29:23,859
Say, for the few who truly have a weight problem, the reason most do it is to get back their youthful shape or to rein in their insatiable appetite.

282
00:29:25,003 --> 00:29:39,042
Such people are forever in that exhausting tug of war only the self can invent, at one time feasting as if there's no tomorrow, and then bloated and obese, dieting because there might very well not be.

283
00:29:40,865 --> 00:29:46,252
In olden days, when our society was more spiritually bound, dieting was called fasting.

284
00:29:47,313 --> 00:29:56,391
But the reason for fasting was not for worldly gains of health and beauty, but to tame the will to undo conditionings forged by greed.

285
00:29:58,255 --> 00:30:07,093
The Buddha instituted for his order members and any lay member who wanted to increase their spiritual effort the rule not to take food after midday.

286
00:30:08,525 --> 00:30:11,729
We don't have to stop eating altogether to practice renunciation.

287
00:30:12,609 --> 00:30:17,277
For the reason is to let go of all conditioning of eating for greed and not for nourishment.

288
00:30:18,557 --> 00:30:19,880
Not to let go of food itself.

289
00:30:21,321 --> 00:30:24,826
This is the difference between renunciation and self-mortification.

290
00:30:25,968 --> 00:30:31,535
The self-mortifier blames his body for his greed and so denies the body what it needs.

291
00:30:32,836 --> 00:30:35,140
The renunciator blames attitude.

292
00:30:36,875 --> 00:30:38,336
Take the bad habit of snacking.

293
00:30:39,298 --> 00:30:47,070
Rather than blame the body and go on long punitive diets, better to sit quietly with the craving and wait for it to pass.

294
00:30:48,333 --> 00:30:53,402
Or if that's difficult, put the mind onto something more skillful such as taking a walk.

295
00:30:54,462 --> 00:31:00,553
And that's the main reason for not eating after midday on this course, to investigate greed and to let it go.

296
00:31:02,592 --> 00:31:11,627
Remember, every time we let go of an unskillful conditioning, we also strengthen our will to follow the Dharma, our Dhamma Chaitanya.

297
00:31:12,769 --> 00:31:18,660
And as I'm sure you've all experienced, there's the added advantage of being a little more awake in the evening.

298
00:31:20,362 --> 00:31:24,366
The same practice can decondition any unwholesome habit we have.

299
00:31:25,449 --> 00:31:27,811
Just think how addicted we become to the TV.

300
00:31:28,472 --> 00:31:29,413
Now how to tackle that?

301
00:31:30,355 --> 00:31:40,388
Well, if you want to hit it head on, just sit in front of the box with a cup of tea and biscuit, and when your favourite programme comes on, don't switch the TV on.

302
00:31:41,490 --> 00:31:43,794
Just sit there and watch the inner programme.

303
00:31:44,694 --> 00:31:45,896
Now that's spiritual training.

304
00:31:47,782 --> 00:31:49,786
And this is where our free choice really lies.

305
00:31:50,606 --> 00:31:57,075
Free choice here is not some anarchic behaviour, do as I want to do, when I want to do and how I want to do.

306
00:31:57,435 --> 00:31:58,717
That's how the self would have it.

307
00:31:59,719 --> 00:32:01,260
But we don't live in our own universe.

308
00:32:01,840 --> 00:32:03,083
We aren't creator gods.

309
00:32:04,585 --> 00:32:09,612
Choice arises when the possibility of two or more actions arise in a given situation.

310
00:32:10,833 --> 00:32:12,434
Most of our lives we have little choice.

311
00:32:13,236 --> 00:32:16,119
We have to get up to work, we have to go to bed to rest and so on.

312
00:32:17,669 --> 00:32:20,854
But there are many sorts of choices we do have to make.

313
00:32:21,134 --> 00:32:25,622
Some are trivial, to have tea or coffee, walk this way around the park.

314
00:32:25,642 --> 00:32:28,606
Some are practical, pragmatic, the best way to buy a house.

315
00:32:29,788 --> 00:32:35,699
But for the trainee, choices become important when there is an ethical or spiritual value to them.

316
00:32:37,201 --> 00:32:42,951
Ethics is concerned with the way we treat ourselves and other human beings, or living beings and the earth.

317
00:32:44,280 --> 00:32:48,392
Spiritual decisions are more personal and concern our own inner growth.

318
00:32:50,016 --> 00:32:55,450
Once we've made a decision and empowered it, we've created an act of thought, word or deed.

319
00:32:56,132 --> 00:32:58,357
And whether we like it or not, there will be a result.

320
00:32:59,704 --> 00:33:14,762
So what we come to understand is that there is no absolutely free will and that ultimately our choices are whether to empower those thoughts, desires, intentions that lead to suffering or those that lead to the end of suffering.

321
00:33:15,984 --> 00:33:27,618
So that we can say that the process of awakening, of liberation as it shapes our characters and personalities is simply the switch from unwholesome habits to wholesome ones.

322
00:33:29,692 --> 00:33:33,458
Here we come to the other core teaching of the Buddha concerning karma.

323
00:33:34,739 --> 00:33:48,839
Many people these days don't believe that.

324
00:33:49,540 --> 00:33:52,746
That's why there's an attitude of, well, if you can get away with it, all the better.

325
00:33:54,278 --> 00:34:00,585
Even in the Buddha's day, there was a famous teacher who said it was irrelevant what you did by way of good or bad deeds.

326
00:34:01,026 --> 00:34:03,648
Your karma, meaning your destiny here, was set.

327
00:34:04,869 --> 00:34:17,164
He said if you went down one side of the Ganges and murdered, pillaged and created mayhem, or whether you came up the other side performing immense deeds of compassion, it would not make a blind bit of difference.

328
00:34:19,253 --> 00:34:25,579
Now two of the great insights the Buddha had upon enlightenment were concerned with this sort of karma.

329
00:34:27,001 --> 00:34:37,614
The first was that he saw all his past lives and saw clearly how all the ethical and spiritual decisions he had made had led to his becoming a fully self-enlightened Buddha.

330
00:34:39,476 --> 00:34:46,003
And then he also saw beings moving from one realm to another according to their ethical and spiritual decisions.

331
00:34:47,215 --> 00:34:53,384
What had been seen first of all as a personal individual law was now understood to be a cosmic law.

332
00:34:53,643 --> 00:34:55,527
It was true for all beings.

333
00:34:57,630 --> 00:34:59,472
Now here we seem to have a contradiction.

334
00:35:00,014 --> 00:35:05,041
At one time we are saying that the situation we find ourselves is not entirely of our own making.

335
00:35:06,222 --> 00:35:08,987
And you hear the Buddha seems to be saying as much.

336
00:35:09,693 --> 00:35:25,974
To clarify this situation we must understand that although the world out there has its own relative existence and reality it remains even when we are not here what we experience of it and how we relate to that experience is all of our own creation.

337
00:35:28,338 --> 00:35:31,382
When we came here to join this course we all saw this building.

338
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:39,311
No one will deny this building exists and has some objective reality yet did we see the same building?

339
00:35:40,608 --> 00:35:48,063
Is it not true that each of us had a different image, a different feeling, a different understanding of the place, even if only in delicate shades?

340
00:35:49,565 --> 00:36:00,068
In other words, Buddhism teaches that even if the world out there has some objective reality of its own, we only know it from our own subjective perspectives.

341
00:36:01,853 --> 00:36:06,280
What seems to have great beauty or meaning to one person strikes another as indifferent.

342
00:36:07,380 --> 00:36:08,983
Think of the arguments of modern art.

343
00:36:09,063 --> 00:36:10,025
Is it art or isn't it?

344
00:36:10,385 --> 00:36:10,867
Who knows?

345
00:36:11,668 --> 00:36:13,690
Well, we could say only the judges know.

346
00:36:14,532 --> 00:36:16,074
But then they only know for themselves.

347
00:36:17,016 --> 00:36:19,840
And if anyone has an opinion, well, that's their judgment.

348
00:36:21,041 --> 00:36:30,155
In this way, there can be no absolute objective standard in art existing out there in the universe that are only agreed conventions among human beings.

349
00:36:32,161 --> 00:36:43,280
So it's not the situation we find ourselves in but the way we are in any given situation that is our karma proper, that karma that pertains to the process of liberation.

350
00:36:44,802 --> 00:36:46,085
Take one of those earthquakes.

351
00:36:46,945 --> 00:36:52,155
There will be some who go through the experience with utter horror and yet others with calmness.

352
00:36:53,538 --> 00:36:56,682
There was the case of a mother and child trapped beneath concrete.

353
00:36:57,371 --> 00:37:02,117
To keep her child alive, the mother cut her fingers and had the child suck her blood.

354
00:37:03,398 --> 00:37:10,967
Right there in the midst of that horror there can arise such selflessness and heroism, whereas no doubt others scream themselves to death.

355
00:37:12,849 --> 00:37:16,893
There are people you meet who have to suffer terrible diseases and misfortune.

356
00:37:17,855 --> 00:37:23,481
Some are emotionally gnarled by the experience, embittered, self-piteous, humorless.

357
00:37:24,271 --> 00:37:28,777
A while back I remember there was a policeman who was shot and lost the power of his legs.

358
00:37:29,699 --> 00:37:34,405
It seems he made a valiant attempt to make sense of his life but eventually committed suicide.

359
00:37:36,268 --> 00:37:42,619
Yet we have the heroic example of many people cruelly paralysed in all limbs and yet still find life meaningful.

360
00:37:44,061 --> 00:37:48,927
I met someone who was so paralysed after a car crash, though happily he did recover.

361
00:37:49,853 --> 00:37:54,717
While lying there it came to him that his life was still, as he put it, authentic.

362
00:37:56,248 --> 00:38:02,657
In other words, how we experience our lives is the way we have conditioned ourselves to experience our lives.

363
00:38:03,760 --> 00:38:08,527
Of course, our parents, family, culture and so on have had enormous influence in the way we see things.

364
00:38:09,467 --> 00:38:13,795
But, and it's hard for us to accept this, they actually only have influence.

365
00:38:14,815 --> 00:38:21,025
Yes, even as utterly vulnerable children, it is still our own decisions that make our conditionings.

366
00:38:22,405 --> 00:38:30,436
Ultimately, it is we who have made the internal decisions that have brought about our particular way of relating to the world.

367
00:38:31,677 --> 00:38:37,987
In the final analysis, then, we must take on the entire responsibility of our own perspectives and attitudes.

368
00:38:39,550 --> 00:38:46,539
And it is because of these perspectives and attitudes that we have created the inner environment in which we continue to live.

369
00:38:47,853 --> 00:38:56,786
So when we feel unhappy, it's an utter waste of time to seek the solution out there, for the fundamental reason lies within our own hearts and minds.

370
00:38:57,706 --> 00:38:59,829
It is futile to seek someone to blame.

371
00:39:02,152 --> 00:39:03,775
At first this may seem unfair.

372
00:39:04,496 --> 00:39:07,661
How could I have known as a baby, as a child, or even as an adult?

373
00:39:08,842 --> 00:39:10,184
But what if it were not so?

374
00:39:11,005 --> 00:39:17,775
If indeed other people can make willful decisions that actually condition my inner attitudes?

375
00:39:18,210 --> 00:39:21,398
then how could I ever change without having to change them also?

376
00:39:23,141 --> 00:39:37,434
Everybody whom I think has conditioned me, rather than influence my conditioning, and by implication all those who conditioned them and so on to all people, everybody would have to be liberated before I myself could attain that liberation.

377
00:39:39,304 --> 00:39:56,132
But when we see that others can only influence our decisions and that we alone are the sole creators of our deeds, then firstly we stop empowering people to dominate us and secondly we take full responsibility for our decisions and our own psychological conditioning.

378
00:39:57,023 --> 00:40:11,960
Now once we do that, we are on the noble path to liberation from all suffering, for we can purify our hearts and clarify our understanding, both necessary preconditions for the attainment of Nibbāna.

379
00:40:14,454 --> 00:40:31,434
So now we've talked about the fundamental laws of conditioning how we live in uncertain times all the time for we do not know what lines of events will come together for us in any given moment that's indeed why the Buddha told us not to try to work out our karma it would drive us mad

380
00:40:32,949 --> 00:40:38,503
We talk to the many laws that affect us from nature to genetics, from psychology to family to society.

381
00:40:39,485 --> 00:40:50,233
We discuss the difference between morality and skillfulness, how the former is included in the latter, how skillfulness is the whole noble path that leads to liberation.

382
00:40:51,731 --> 00:40:56,097
We saw how the Buddha puts his finger so firmly on the role of will in our conditioning.

383
00:40:57,139 --> 00:41:10,637
And finally, how there is an underlying moral law within the universe that dictates that unwholesome actions will have negative effects and wholesome actions positive effects within our own psyches.

384
00:41:12,681 --> 00:41:17,588
And it is upon this final note that we need to concentrate, especially in our daily lives.

385
00:41:18,597 --> 00:41:24,708
Why is it that so many people seem to get away with it and so many people don't seem to get their just reward?

386
00:41:25,836 --> 00:41:30,963
It is only when we look inwardly that we see there is a justice based on this moral law.

387
00:41:31,003 --> 00:41:36,190
Remember, the effects of one's actions outwardly can never be determined.

388
00:41:36,992 --> 00:41:38,414
There are too many variables.

389
00:41:39,474 --> 00:41:45,643
But inwardly, all our decisions are going towards creating an ugly or a beautiful environment.

390
00:41:46,784 --> 00:41:54,375
And just because a person may be good at suppressing their guilt, anger, fear and so on, doesn't mean they've escaped them.

391
00:41:54,355 --> 00:42:03,369
These turbulences, as our meditation makes so obvious to us, are always there, lurking in the depths, causing slow havoc in the body.

392
00:42:04,952 --> 00:42:20,717
But worse, they are secretly skewing our perspective of the world, as Freud understood so well, so that we find ourselves falling again and again into the same old situations, the same old problems, the same old traps, the same old unsatisfactoriness.

393
00:42:21,894 --> 00:42:23,175
And it could all be so different.

394
00:42:24,117 --> 00:42:31,766
And it will be different once we take hold of this wild bull and begin to train it in the ways of the true law.

395
00:42:34,228 --> 00:42:37,452
The Buddha warned us that the way is gradual.

396
00:42:38,393 --> 00:42:39,994
It's going to take some time.

397
00:42:40,434 --> 00:42:43,197
Think in terms of decades, not years.

398
00:42:44,259 --> 00:42:47,902
But although the path is hard, it should not be laborious.

399
00:42:48,219 --> 00:42:52,648
Think of the drudgery or training for an Olympic sport.

400
00:42:52,668 --> 00:43:02,027
Every day, for instance, rowers can train for six hours, and most of it rowing, that monotonous movement, forward, backward, forward, backward.

401
00:43:02,934 --> 00:43:08,949
They probably go through days of sheer boredom, I don't know, but they are fired with the will to win.

402
00:43:08,990 --> 00:43:18,936
That same drive to become awakened is called samvāga, translated as a sense of urgency about our task, an enthusiasm.

403
00:43:19,726 --> 00:43:23,391
That's the feeling of Dhamma Chaitanya, the will of the true law.

404
00:43:24,452 --> 00:43:37,532
Though the path ahead of us is hard, tough, demanding real determination and stamina, yet there is a joy to it, a subtle joy, that suffuses the spiritual life, and that joy is hope.

405
00:43:37,512 --> 00:43:42,900
Hope is not expectation, rather expectation is hope with a date put on it.

406
00:43:43,641 --> 00:43:57,545
No, hope is the heart's secret delight when it is informed through faith and insight that there will be a time when we shall enter into that blissful peace and contentment of Nibbana.

407
00:43:57,525 --> 00:44:07,297
It is this hope we should savour and from that heartfelt base we should express our wisdom, little though it may be, into the world.

408
00:44:08,119 --> 00:44:14,666
And in this way everything we do will be perfumed with love, compassion, joy or peace.

409
00:44:18,050 --> 00:44:19,331
Let's pause here for a moment.

410
00:44:47,813 --> 00:44:54,889
And so the connection is made between our training here on an intensive course and our training in ordinary daily life.

411
00:44:56,012 --> 00:45:04,152
If in our understanding there's a hair's breadth of difference between the two, that gap is a chasm that will greatly undermine our progress.

412
00:45:05,887 --> 00:45:16,557
The Mahasi side, or reinforcing the words of the Buddha, moment-to-moment mindfulness is the secret of success, points to the essence of our practice, and that practice is full-time.

413
00:45:17,278 --> 00:45:19,159
Six hours a day just won't do.

414
00:45:20,322 --> 00:45:29,110
Save for the hours of sleep, not a moment should pass when we are not making that effort to be aware, a calm, bright attentiveness.

415
00:45:30,891 --> 00:45:33,614
That's all we have to do to become fully awakened.

416
00:45:34,117 --> 00:45:36,521
It's as easy as that and as hard as that.

417
00:45:37,922 --> 00:45:39,405
But do we have a choice in the matter?

418
00:45:40,186 --> 00:45:42,889
Is there any free will to be exercised here?

419
00:45:43,670 --> 00:45:44,271
Not at all.

420
00:45:44,592 --> 00:45:45,052
Not now.

421
00:45:45,693 --> 00:45:47,556
We all know where the truth lies.

422
00:45:48,117 --> 00:45:48,978
So we have to go on.

423
00:45:49,840 --> 00:45:52,123
There's no way back but to misery.

424
00:45:54,306 --> 00:45:55,708
Here's the Dhammapada again.

425
00:45:57,010 --> 00:46:02,757
Guarding speech, restraining the mind, let no unwholesome action be done.

426
00:46:02,958 --> 00:46:08,248
Purifying these three modes of doing, so the wise realize the path.

427
00:46:09,951 --> 00:46:12,215
Let's take the Buddha's last words to heart.

428
00:46:13,358 --> 00:46:16,242
All compounded things are impermanent.

429
00:46:16,262 --> 00:46:19,670
Strive diligently for your liberation.

430
00:46:21,172 --> 00:46:21,472
Onward.

431
00:46:23,056 --> 00:46:38,181
May your devoted commitment to Dhammachetana, the will of the true law, draw you speedily out of the torrents and whirlpools of crazy self-centeredness into the warm, still waters of Nibbana.

432
00:46:39,523 --> 00:46:42,668
Sooner rather than later.
